<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 93 / UK Company News: British Land 3.9% ahead as property values
pick up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AS WELL as announcing the Pounds 500m property buying partnership and a
Pounds 132m rights issue yesterday, British Land reported a 3.9 per cent
rise in pre-tax profits to Pounds 34.6m for the year to end-March, writes
Maggie Urry.
Mr John Ritblat, chairman, said that 'the signs of recovery which I
signalled a year ago are now more widely discernible'. He said that since
the recession began, the group had bought Pounds 900m of properties and
those were now valued at Pounds 109m over purchase price.
A final dividend of 4.72p (4.28p) is proposed to give a total of 7p (6.35p),
a rise of 10.2 per cent. Fully diluted earnings per share rose 6.4 per cent
to 13.3p.
The fall in the value of the group's properties over the year was 3.3 per
cent, a smaller drop than the 10.5 per cent and 9.6 per cent of the two
previous years. During the year the group bought Pounds 166m of properties
and sold Pounds 113m. Net assets per share fell from 326p to 307p.
Gross rental income rose by 15.3 per cent to Pounds 146.6m, a feature being
the rent review at the Euston Tower, and operating income was up 18.3 per
cent to Pounds 125.5m. There was a Pounds 2.3m (Pounds 6.3m) profit on
property trading.
However, the interest charge rose from Pounds 79.1m to Pounds 93.2m. Mr John
Weston Smith, finance director, said that the debt/equity ratio had been
reduced. Year-end net debt was Pounds 882m and shareholders funds were
Pounds 718.4m (Pounds 763.8m).
The group had exercised its right to convert its Pounds 115m convertible
bonds into convertible preference shares and had issued a Pounds 200m,
35-year debenture. The group also has over Pounds 600m of bank facilities.
The group's debt now has an average maturity of 19 years at an average cost
of 9.58 per cent.
Mr Weston Smith said that there had been a slight increase in the proportion
of voids in the portfolio to 3 per cent, but that 50 per cent of the group's
properties were occupied either by government agencies or FT-SE 100
companies.
The UK office portfolio had fallen in value by 12.2 per cent, but within
that City of London offices had fallen by 11.4 per cent compared with a 31
per cent drop the previous year.
</TEXT>
