<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 93 / Observer: Fail-safe
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Only in Italy can a transport minister, who fails his driving test, be
hailed as some sort of folk hero.
One of the very first things that Italy's new transport minister, Raffaele
Costa, did on taking up his post was to sit his country's new written
driving test along with the rest of his 54-strong parliamentary Transport
Commission. He had been deluged with complaints about trick questions and
the general difficulty of the examination. So he took the 30-question test,
requiring answers of true or false, and got eight questions wrong. No more
than four mistakes are allowed if a person is to pass.
Costa blames the exam rather than his lack of road knowledge and promises to
simplify the questionnaire. His growing band of supporters is hoping that
his next posting might be to Italy's finance ministry where he will be
required to take on an even more daunting challenge - filling in an Italian
tax form without making a mistake.
</TEXT>
