<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 93 / Business levy urged for rail projects
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A LEVY on London businesses could help finance transport investment in
CrossRail, the Jubilee Line extension to Docklands and other rail and
Underground projects, says London First, the business-led initiative set up
last year to promote strategic thinking about the capital.
The proposal has been prepared by London First's 16-strong transport group,
which is chaired by Mr Peter Foy, the senior partner of management
consultants McKinsey.
The Department of Transport last night described the proposal as
'interesting and deserving of further consideration'.
London First estimates that more than Pounds 17bn will be needed over the
next 10 years to fund the renewal of London's rail and Underground systems
and to finance new projects. Current government investment plans will
provide only 50 per cent of what is needed over the next five years.
The group's proposal involves creating an organisation, called the London
Transport Funding Trust, to top up government funds. It would draw its
income from a levy on businesses - perhaps through an addition to the
uniform business rate. The trust would raise capital for transport
investment by issuing bonds, servicing the debt from the levy.
Mr Foy said: 'A 1p increase in the business rate would raise over Pounds
100m, enough to support approximately Pounds 1bn in bonds. We feel that this
is a big enough sum to make a difference to investment in London
infrastructure and small enough not to scare off the private sector.'
The trust would be majority-owned by the private sector, and run by a board
to represent London businesses. Its borrowing would therefore be outside the
public sector borrowing requirement, which the government is struggling to
constrain. The new funds would provide the private sector with a leadership
role in transport investment, according to Mr Foy. It would provide a
catalyst for ensuring the timely implementation of priority investments, he
said.
Mr Foy believes that business would support such a levy if the government
committed itself to a long-term agreed investment programme to upgrade the
capital's infrastructure.
</TEXT>
