<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 93 / Accounts board warns on rules
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPANIES MUST obey the spirit and reasoning of the new accounting standards
in almost every circumstance if their accounts are to comply with the law,
according to draft documents issued yesterday by the Accounting Standards
Board.
Members of UK accounting bodies who are directors or officers of companies
are also required to ensure their fellow officers understand the
significance of the drafts, it says.
The details come in two documents which stress that the standards issued by
the board and its urgent-issues task force are underpinned in law. They
include a legal opinion from Ms Mary Arden, a senior commercial barrister
recently appointed a judge, who says the courts are likely to accept the
guidelines.
That view gives significant new authority to the board compared with its
predecessor, the Accounting Standards Committee. Mr David Tweedie, chairman
of the board, said: 'This is a great leap forward. Before we could not
move.'
A separate foreword says abstracts from the board's urgent-issues task force
are part of the standards which help meet the requirement in law that
accounts show 'a true and fair view'.
The forward also says that companies should adopt the standards as soon as
possible.
It stresses that there will normally be no scope for 'grandfathering' of
transactions - by which companies can exempt transactions from new standards
if they took place before the standards were introduced.
Foreword to accounting standards. Accountancy Books, PO Box 620, Central
Milton Keynes, MK9 2JX. Pounds 5.
</TEXT>
