<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 93 / Draft puts greater onus on principal auditors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PRINCIPAL auditors to companies must ensure that they are satisfied with
the adequacy of work carried out by other auditors used during an audit,
under draft guidelines issued yesterday by the Auditing Practices Board.
The quality of work must be considered when using affiliates, correspondent
firms and unrelated firms in the UK or overseas.
Auditors must consider the 'materiality of the statements they audit' to the
group accounts, their knowledge of the business and their relationship with
affiliated firms before accepting appointment as principal auditors, it
says.
The details come in SAS 510 on the relationship between principal and other
auditors, one of five draft standards issued yesterday by the board.
Mr John Hennessy, of accountants Arthur Andersen, who is a member of the
board, said: 'This is just a matter, we hope, of putting what is sensible
good practice down on to paper.'
SAS 100, the statement on objective and general principles, says auditors
should comply with auditing standards, and obtain sufficient evidence to
determine whether the statements are free of material misstatement and
prepared in accordance with legislation and accounting standards.
SAS 470, on the review of financial statements, says auditors must consider
whether the presentation of accounts has been unduly influenced by
management's desire to present facts in a favourable or unfavourable light,
and the effects of the aggregation of uncorrected misstatements.
SAS 500, on the work of internal audit, for the first time places an
obligation on auditors to look at the activities of internal audit and the
effect on external audit, and to liaise with the internal auditors.
The board has invited comments on the drafts by the end of September, and
will publish a collection of draft standards by the end of October.
SAS 100, 470, 500, 510, 520. Accountancy Books, PO Box 620, Central Milton
Keynes, MK9 2JX. Pounds 1.50 each.
</TEXT>
