<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 93 / Fall feared in mortgage applications
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SHARP fall in the number of young people applying for mortgages later this
decade was predicted yesterday, following the publication of research on how
attitudes have been affected by falls in property prices in the past three
years.
The Building Societies Association disclosed internal research showing a
fall in the number of people aged between 16 and 34 who regard
owner-occupation within two years as their ideal, and a substantial rise in
those favouring private rented homes.
Mr Adrian Coles, director-general designate of the BSA, told its annual
conference in Brighton that the change in attitude, combined with a fall in
the number of people in their mid-20s, could lead to 'a very significant
reduction' in mortgage applications.
Mr Coles said the change was not surprising. 'It is younger people who will
have obtained relatively large mortgages in the late 1980s, found high
interest rates most difficult to cope with, and have been or are likely to
be frustrated movers,' he said.
He said that the average age of entry to owner-occupation could rise by
three or four years, and this could lead to 'a difficult three or four years
in the marketplace while the average age is increasing'.
Mr Coles emphasised, however, that the research, which was carried out in
February and March among 2,500 people, had shown that the overall proportion
favouring owner-occupation within two years had recovered to its peak 1989
level of 81 per cent after falling to 77 per cent in 1991.
The proportion of 16 to 24 year olds favouring owner-occupation within two
years fell from 79 per cent in 1989 to 60 per cent in 1991 and only partly
recovered to 71 per cent by this year. Among 25 to 34 year olds it fell from
89 per cent to 83 per cent before recovering to 84 per cent.
Mr Coles said that the views of younger people were 'unfortunately' more
influential than those of the elderly in determining the housing market
because they moved more frequently and were more likely to become first-time
buyers.
The study found a large rise in the proportion of young people favouring
rented accommodation. In 1989 only 4 per cent of 20 to 24 year olds aspired
to this, but the proportion more than doubled to 11 per cent this year.
Mr Coles said many young people had been put off owner-occupation because
there was no longer a prospect of increases in house prices sharp enough to
cover the transaction costs of moving home.
Mr John Wriglesworth, housing analyst at UBS, said the prospect of a fall in
the number of first-time buyers in the late 1990s meant that the government
should not take measures which would stifle housing demand excessively.
</TEXT>
