<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 93 / ITC to reopen Channel 5 debate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Independent Television Commission plans to reopen the debate about the
future of Channel 5 next month with the publication of a report setting out
a range of options.
The idea of a fifth national television channel appeared to die in December,
when the ITC rejected the only bidder, a consortium led by Thames
Television.
The ITC said that it was not satisfied with the consortium's business plan
nor its level of 'investor commitment.'
For the past few months ITC engineers have been reconsidering the technical
possibilities for a fifth channel. The commission believes that a new
channel is still a distinct possibility.
The most expensive stumbling block to last year's proposal was the fact that
the Channel 5 signal would have caused interference to millions of video
recorders.
The first of three main options outlined by the report would reduce the need
to retune video recorders by proposing extra frequencies for the channel.
The second option suggests using frequencies once considered for a sixth
television channel to set up a series of city-based television stations.
That option would require legislation as the 1990 Broadcasting Act provides
for a national Channel 5.
The third main option is receiving increasing attention. It suggests using
the Channel 5 frequencies to launch digital television in the UK. Using
digital technology at least four channels can be squeezed into the space now
occupied by one.
That could, at least in theory, allow the creation of several new services
or could be used to launch wider screen television, although viewers would
need a special box to convert the signal.
The ITC plans to invite comments on the options and call for expressions of
interest, and may re-advertise the channel before the end of this year or
early next year.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Channel 5 Holdings.
</CO>
<XX>
