<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 93 / Rise in late construction payments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORE THAN 60 per cent of construction contracts are paid late, according to
a study to be published this week.
The findings, which indicate that late payments owed to construction
suppliers last year totalled Pounds 19bn, will give fresh impetus to demands
from government and business organisations for companies to improve their
payment performance.
The Confederation of British Industry has said late payment is one of the
main causes of business failures. The Institute of Directors last week
called for improved court procedures to help small companies fighting to get
paid on time.
Construction Intelligence Data, an independent research and credit rating
organisation, has examined the experiences of about 1,000 sub-contractors.
Its findings, to be published this week, show that the record of
construction companies, renowned as some of the worst payers in UK industry,
has deteriorated even further in the past 12 months.
According to the findings the proportion of contracts involving late
payments jumped from an average of 45 per cent in the year to March 31 1992
to more than 60 per cent in the following 12 months. It is estimated that 90
per cent, or Pounds 31.5bn, of the Pounds 35bn spent annually on
construction in the UK is channelled through specialist sub-contractors.
Sub-contractors say that financially hard-pressed main contractors are
holding on to cash as long as possible instead of passing on payments from
developers and building owners to the sub-contractors actually doing the
work.
Their biggest concern is that contractors may fail before making payments.
In these circumstances sub-contractors which have already spent money doing
work can quickly follow the main contractor into receivership.
The findings show that the average number of days for which payment was
delayed, after the date agreed in the contract, had risen from 13 to 28
since the end of March last year.
They also show that main contractors were automatically deducting discounts
designed to encourage prompt payments, even when payments were late. Almost
three quarters of late payments had discounts incorrectly deducted.
It is estimated that nearly Pounds 350m had been incorrectly deducted, based
on an average discount of 2.5 per cent of the contract value. The
researchers say the number of sub-contractors starting legal action against
late or incorrect payment had risen sharply.
</TEXT>
<XX>
