<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 93 / Lloyd's judge to expedite actions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER and JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JUSTICE SAVILLE, the High Court judge, is to step up efforts to
rationalise an increasingly complex set of legal actions involving Lloyd's
Names in the face of growing congestion in the Commercial Court.
Some observers believe that this could give a fillip to efforts by Lloyd's
to achieve an out-of-court settlement.
Mr Saville, head of the Commercial Court, will meet solicitors representing
groups of Names - the individuals whose capital backs the insurance market -
and their agents on June 21 and 22. It is understood that he is unwilling to
set new court dates for any Lloyd's cases until he has formed an overall
view of the issues.
Mr David Bird, clerk to the Commercial Court, said: 'Part of the reason for
the meetings is to find out the scale of the problems. We know a lot of
Lloyd's cases are floating about but we do not know how many or what impact
they will have.'
Parties who have not yet decided to take legal action will also be invited
to the meeting, which is being organised by Elborne Mitchell, the
solicitors.
It is also understood that Sir Michael Kerr, the former High Court judge and
privy counsellor heading Lloyd's efforts to obtain an out-of-court
settlement, will also attend the meeting. Mr Saville has asked permission
from parties involved in the disputes to meet with Sir Michael separately.
Last week Mr Saville met solicitors representing Names taking individual
action.
More than two dozen groups of Names have launched or are considering action
against their agents as part of efforts to recover insurance losses. So far
only a handful of cases has come to court, although a case by several
thousand members of the Feltrim syndicates, who are applying for a summary
judgment in their case against agents, is set to come to court in September.
To complicate matters Mr Saville is scheduled to preside in a big
non-Lloyd's case in the autumn which could last up to a year.
Earlier this year Mr Saville issued a strong warning that unless more judges
were appointed to the over-pressed Commercial Court Britain could lose its
position as a leading centre for international litigation, costing the UK
legal profession millions of pounds.
In response to his demands - and obvious pressure on other parts of the High
Court - the Lord Chancellor has undertaken to appoint a further 10 judges by
the autumn, some of whom will take charge of Commercial Court cases.
</TEXT>
