FT  03 JUN 93 / BA seeks meeting with union leader
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TALKS aimed at averting a strike by British Airways cabin crews and ground
staff were adjourned yesterday, with management maintaining that some
progress had been made.
BA is now seeking a meeting with Mr Bill Morris, general secretary of the
TGWU general union, in an effort to resolve the dispute over pay and
conditions.
'Talks were constructive and we made definite progress on one issue and now
seek further talks on the outstanding issue,' the airline said.
A union spokesman, however, said there was still 'a big chasm between both
sides'.
The dispute arose following the introduction of new pay and conditions for
staff at Gatwick Airport following BA's takeover of Dan-Air last year.
The main issue, which is over conditions for BA's Gatwick staff, remains to
be resolved.
Yesterday's meeting lasted five hours, and followed a ballot of TGWU members
last week which resulted in 62 per cent voting for a strike.
No immediate action was taken by the union but Mr Morris said that if no
agreement was reached a strike would be called.
The TGWU was not commenting on the talks last night. It is understood the
union does not want to say anything ahead of the proposed meeting between BA
and Mr Morris.
The result of a ballot of 3,000 BA pilots on industrial action over what
they claim is an attempt to introduce poorer pay and conditions is expected
to be announced on Friday.
</TEXT>
