<PROFILE>_AN-DFCCOABRFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930603
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 93 / Budget delays healthcare reform plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Bill Clinton is delaying release of his healthcare reform plan in
order to concentrate on winning Senate approval for his deficit-cutting
economic plan, the White House indicated yesterday.
Mr Clinton said he did not expect a 'sustained delay', but refused to set a
date for publication of the healthcare plan.
'I'm focused right now on passing the budget in the Senate,' he said, adding
that the administration intended to remove as many kinks from the plan as
possible before sending it to Congress.
The Senate is unlikely to vote on the economic plan until the beginning of
July so the health plan is likely to be delayed until at least mid-July.
However, this would be only a fortnight before the August recess and the
plan may be postponed until September.
Mr Clinton originally promised to send the healthcare reform proposal to
Congress within 100 days of his inauguration. It was then delayed, first to
mid-May and then to the middle of this month.
The latest delay reflects the tough fight the administration faces in the
Senate if it is to pass the economic plan without too many concessions. Mr
Clinton said this week he would accept a shift in emphasis from tax
increases to spending cuts.
But a delay is also opportune because Mr Clinton has yet to make crucial
decisions on the shape of the healthcare reform. The administration is still
debating the nature of the benefits to be guaranteed, the details of reforms
to the insurance system and the plan's finance.
Some advisers want a payroll tax on employers and employees to displace
corporate health premiums.
</TEXT>
