FT  03 JUN 93 / Burundi's president concedes defeat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUJUMBURA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Pierre Buyoya, unexpectedly defeated in Burundi's first democratic
election, congratulated his victorious opponent, Mr Melchior Ndadaye,
yesterday and urged the country to accept the result, Reuter reports from
Bujumbura.
'You have just chosen your president, who will lead Burundi for the next
five years,' Mr Buyoya said in a statement read on state radio. 'As I said
before embarking on the race, I undertook to bow before the verdict of the
people. That is the rule of democracy.'
Official provisional results gave Mr Ndadaye, a 40-year-old banker, 60 per
cent of the vote, confounding forecasts that Mr Buyoya would win by a
similar margin to extend the presidency he seized in a bloodless coup in
1987.
Mr Ndadaye is from the majority Hutu tribe, which has been governed for
decades by the Tutsi minority, of which Mr Buyoya is a member.
It was the first democratic election in the central African state since
independence from Belgium in 1962.
The history of the state since independence has been marred by the slaughter
of hundreds of thousands of people, mostly Hutu killed for challenging their
Tutsi masters.
</TEXT>
