<DATE>930603
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 93 / Bomb defused in Rome near PM's office
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ROME police yesterday defused a car bomb placed in a narrow street within
200 yards of the prime minister's office and parliament. Mr Carlo Azeglio
Ciampi, prime minister, who was in talks with representatives of unions and
employers, declined to evacuate his office and pressed ahead with the
meeting.
The authorities immediately claimed the incident was part of a campaign to
destabilise Italy. It followed the two car bombs in Rome and Florence since
May 14, killing five people and damaging the famed Uffizi Gallery.
The discovery of yesterday's bomb in the heart of Rome at midday has
increased the pressure on the authorities to pinpoint those behind the
campaign. The two previous car bombs have been blamed on the Mafia but there
is a strong suspicion that elements of the security services - long linked
to right-wing extremist groups and the secret Masonic lodge P2 - might be
involved.
The government is understood to be considering ways of reorganising the
security services, which have always been a law unto themselves.
'It is no accident,' commented Mr Ugo Pecchioli, deputy of the Party of the
Democratic Left, 'that every time in Italy's recent history there begins to
be a change in the existing balance of power, events occur like this
morning's which seek to condition the democratic outcome.'
The recently stolen car involved in yesterday's incident contained 20kg of a
mixture of ammonium nitrate and petrol, plus a detonator. Such a mixture has
been used by neo-Fascist groups in Tuscany and is different from that
employed in the Rome and Florence attacks.
Responsibility for planting the bomb was claimed by Armed Falange, the same
organisation which said it was behind the two previous bombs; but the
authorities have so far not taken these calls seriously.
Officials said the car bomb appeared deliberately timed to coincide with
yesterday's celebrations of Republic Day (the first car bomb went off on
National Police Day).
Although the Mafia is being linked to the destabilising campaign, the
government yesterday was able to announce another success against Cosa
Nostra, the umbrella organisation of the Sicilian Mafia. Security forces
arrested Mr Giuseppe Pulvirenti, the most wanted boss in eastern Sicily and
head of a well-armed clan in the Catania region. He had been on the run for
11 years.
His arrest followed that of Mr Nito Santapaola on May 18, the acknowledged
boss of the Catania Mafia and the most wanted man in Sicily following the
arrest in January of Mr 'Toto' Riina, considered the 'boss of bosses'. The
arrest also underlined the crackdown under way in Sicily both against Cosa
Nostra and those with links to it.
</TEXT>
