<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 93 / Soros Pounds 284m investment excites property market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER and MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PROPERTY shares rose sharply yesterday after Mr George Soros announced plans
to invest Pounds 284m in the stricken UK property market.
Mr Soros, the international fund manager reputed to have made Pounds 1bn
betting on a devaluation of sterling in the run up to Black Wednesday and
who in April invested Dollars 400m (Pounds 260m) in a gold mining company,
is forming a Pounds 500m partnership with British Land, the fourth biggest
UK property company.
Mr John Ritblat, British Land chairman, said yesterday's deal underlined his
commitment to the sector's recovery. He said 'signs of recovery . . . are
now more widely discernible'. The deal with Quantum Group, a Dollars 9bn
investment management company advised by Mr Soros, would give 'additional
firepower'.
Mr Ritblat claimed a year ago to have seen a turnaround in the UK property
market, where values have slumped during the recession. He said he had
approached Mr Soros 'a couple of months ago' with the plan. Mr Soros reacted
quickly, he said.
Mr Soros tied up a deal in February with the Reichmann brothers, the
Canadian property developers, to invest in North American property, and in
January he took a 3 per cent stake in Berkeley, the UK housebuilder.
British Land and Quantum are each putting up Pounds 250m, which will be used
to buy a portfolio of properties by the end of 1997. The partnership is
expected to be wound up by 2003. British Land will receive a fee rising to
Pounds 5m a year for managing the portfolio, although both parties will
agree investment decisions.
Quantum is subscribing to 11.3m new shares in British Land, costing Pounds
33.7m, which would give it a 4.8 per cent stake in the company. Quantum will
sell some of these shares to Mr Ritblat and place 4m shares into a British
Land employee trust.
Yesterday's agreement by two such influential investors was seen in the
stockmarket as underlining recovery hopes in the commercial property market.
Falling interest rates and expectations of economic recovery have already
pushed property shares higher. The sector has almost doubled in value since
last September.
The property sector yesterday showed a further 6 per cent rise, with British
Land shares rising 46p to 344p. The market was also excited by the thought
that some of the funds could be used to finance a takeover in the sector.
However, questions were being raised last night over an agreement under
which Mr Ritblat will buy British Land shares from Quantum at 298p,
Tuesday's closing price, and over possible conflicts of interest.
Some investors were concerned about the profit Mr Ritblat would appear to
make on the shares, but British Land defended the deal saying Mr Soros
wanted Mr Ritblat 'to put his money where his mouth is'.
Mr Ritblat is required to hold 4m British Land shares for a year and 2m
shares until the end of 1997.
British Land also announced a Pounds 132m rights issue yesterday to help
finance its share in the partnership with Quantum. The issue is underwritten
by SG Warburg.
The company also reported profits for the year to March 31 up 3.9 per cent
to Pounds 34.6m.
Expensive vote of confidence, Page 21
Lex, Page 22
British Land results, Page 24
London stocks, Page 46
</TEXT>
