<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Sharp fall in bond yields
elevates Dow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
ENCOURAGED by a big fall in bond yields, US share prices posted solid gains
yesterday as investors brushed off disappointing news on the economy, writes
Patrick Harverson in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average closed 24.91 up at 3,552.34, within three
points of its all-time high, set last week. The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 ended
3.64 higher at 453.83, while the Nasdaq composite appreciated 3.75 to
704.28. Trading volume on the New York SE came to 230.7m shares.
After the holiday weekend, traders and investors returned to the markets in
subdued mood. Sentiment was not helped by the morning's main economic news,
the National Association of Purchasing Management's May report, which showed
that its index of manufacturing activity rose only slightly last month to
51.1 per cent. The rise was smaller than expected as analysts had forecast a
level of 53.2 per cent.
One aspect of the report that was particularly troubling was the decline in
the employment component. Coming just a few days before the May jobs report
is released, the decline suggested that labour market conditions remain
depressed throughout the economy.
The bad news on employment, and the fall in the NAPM's inflation indicator,
however, cheered Treasury market investors, who pushed bond prices higher
and yields sharply lower. At one point the bond rally, also partly triggered
by falling gold prices, sent the Dow into record territory, but late selling
trimmed the gain for the index.
Bally Manufacturing jumped Dollars 1 7/8 to Dollars 9 3/8 in volume of 4.2m
shares after the company said it planned to build a second dockside casino
in Mississippi.
Commodore International plunged Dollars 1 to Dollars 3 in heavy trading
after reporting a fiscal third-quarter loss of Dollars 5.37 a share,
compared with the 12 cents a share profit earned a year earlier.
Motor issues were higher on news of a rise in consumer spending. Ford firmed
Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 53, Chrysler Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 45 1/4 and
General Motors Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 40 3/8 .
Raytheon put on Dollars  7/8 at Dollars 55 3/4 on news that the defence
contractor had bought the corporate jet business of British Aerospace for
about Dollars 387m.
McDonald's moved up Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 50 1/8 after Mr Michael Quinlan,
the chairman and chief executive, revealed that the company was considering
the possibility of splitting the common stock and said he was bullish about
business prospects.
On the Nasdaq market, technology shares were stronger, Intel adding Dollars
4 5/8 at Dollars 115 1/2 , Microsoft Dollars 3 5/8 at Dollars 96 1/4 and
Oracle Systems Dollars 2 1/2 at Dollars 44 1/4 .
Canada
TORONTO was weighed down by a sharply retreating gold shares sector, the TSE
300 index finishing 25.8 off at 3,856.9. However, advancing issues narrowly
outnumbered declines by 390 to 374 after heavy volume of 69.8m shares valued
at CDollars 553m.
The golds sub-group index dropped 4.6 per cent as the precious metal price
in New York fell USDollars 8.25 to USDollars 369.75 an ounce amid
profit-taking. Real estate had the day's biggest gain, 1.1 per cent, while
the energy sector rose 1.0 per cent.
Among golds, American Barrick tumbled CDollars 1 3/8 to CDollars 28 and
Placer Dome CDollars 1 1/8 to CDollars 21 3/4.
