<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 93 / International Company News: Rise in fee income helps Royal
Bank of Canada advance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A SHARP rise in fee and investment banking income as well as lower loan loss
provisions helped Royal Bank of Canada lift second-quarter earnings by
almost 15 per cent.
The bank, Canada's largest financial institution, posted earnings of
CDollars 243m (USDollars 192m), or 64 cents a share, in the three months to
April 30, up from CDollars 212m, or 59 cents, a year earlier. Return on
equity climbed to 13.7 per cent from 11.6 per cent.
Assets rose by 4 per cent to CDollars 143.4bn, giving a return on assets of
0.72 per cent, up from 0.64 per cent.
RBC painted a mildly encouraging picture of the loan losses which have
dogged Canadian banks for the past two years.
The estimate of 1993 write-downs is being maintained at CDollars 820m, with
the remaining CDollars 325m of a general reserve set up last year being
allocated to specific accounts.
Mr Allan Taylor, chairman, said he was encouraged by the dip in
non-performing loans to CDollars 3.57bn on April 30 from CDollars 3.84bn
three months earlier. The bulk of the decline was due to the return to
performing status of loans to Argentina.
However, Mr Taylor noted non-performing loans to other borrowers edged down
by CDollars 15m, against a CDollars 300m jump in the previous quarter. A
further deterioration in the commercial property portfolio was offset by an
improvement in other corporate loans and a stabilised retail portfolio.
Interest income was little changed, but fee income climbed by 15 per cent to
CDollars 512m. Earnings of 76 per cent-owned RBC Dominion Securities doubled
to almost CDollars 30m.
RBC also announced a private placement of CDollars 110m of subordinated
debentures. The securities qualify as Tier 2 capital, and will boost the
bank's total capital-to-assets ratio to 10.3 per cent from 9.5 per cent
three months earlier. Under US regulatory guidelines, the bank's total
capital ratio is now 10.2 per cent.
</TEXT>
