<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 93 / UK Company News: Bristol Evening Post at Pounds 4.1m and
cautious for this year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COST-CUTTING helped to boost profits at Bristol Evening Post, the regional
newspaper group which recently shrugged off Mr David Sullivan, its long-time
hostile shareholder and Sunday Sport publisher.
The group announced a 22 per cent jump in pre-tax profits to Pounds 4.1m on
sales 1 per cent lower at Pounds 60.6m for the year to March 31. The figures
compared with profits of Pounds 3.35m on turnover of Pounds 61.4m.
The profit advance was helped by the introduction of FRS 3 which resulted in
the comparative profits being restated downwards. Last year's reported
figure was Pounds 4.06m.
Mr Stanley Clarke, chairman, said the loss of 122 production and
distribution jobs had resulted in a Pounds 1.14m reduction in staff costs.
However, the company was still cautious on trading for the present year. Mr
Clarke said both advertising and circulation were running at lower levels
than last year.
'The recovery will be slow,' he said. 'The current situation is still
erratic.' As a result, the final proposed dividend is being maintained at
7.75p, making a total for the year of 11.75p, a 2 per cent advance on last
year's 11.5p. Earnings per share were 1.2p ahead at 11p.
The group took a Pounds 1.8m charge to pay for the costs of the
reorganisation, which was offset by a Pounds 1.6m profit on the sale of
investments.
