<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 93 / Clinton ready to compromise on deficit proposals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Bill Clinton yesterday declared he was willing to accept smaller
tax increases and deeper spending cuts in order to get his deficit reduction
plan through Congress.
In a speech conspicuous for its bipartisan tone, he said the US must 'move
beyond entitlement and abandonment'. Democrats had to accept that not all
cherished social programmes could be fully funded, as in the past, while
Republicans should recognise that it was impossible 'to abandon the cities'.
The address to a lunch organised by conservative and other groups in
Milwaukee, a blue collar Democratic city, was replete with campaign-style
pleas for a new political consensus. Washington, he said, had to forget
'brain dead politics from either party' and seize 'the historic moment to
regain control of our economic destiny'.
He did not specify which of his proposed new taxes might be cut and where
spending might be reduced more sharply. Indeed, he continued to defend his
overall programme as 'balanced and fair'. But it is widely assumed that the
proposed energy tax will not emerge from the Senate later this month in
anything like the broad-based form in which it passed the House last week.
Mr Clinton's willingness to compromise on the energy tax has already
elicited optimistic forecasts from conservative Democratic critics such as
oil-state senators David Boren of Oklahoma and John Breaux of Louisiana that
an amended budget package stands a fair chance in the Senate. The
prospective change in the tax and spending mix of his proposals may also
appeal to some moderate Republican senators.
Mr Clinton received some support for his attack on the federal deficit from
the independent Congressional Budget Office yesterday, which reported that
his proposals would 'curtail but not arrest' growth in the national debt and
interest payments.
His pitch on the need for greater investment was also underlined by mixed
economic data which pointed, at best, to only weak expansion last month. The
purchasing managers index showed a modest increase to 51.1 per cent from the
49.7 per cent of April, but statistics on personal income and construction
spending showed no changes in April compared with March.
US growth picks up, Page 7
See Lex
</TEXT>
