FT  02 JUN 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It is Derby Day and Channel 4 will show us the race live at 3.45, and all
the main events from Epsom in Derby Highlights at 11.05. But it is also the
40th anniversary of the coronation, and it is going to be difficult to
avoid. BBC1 begins at 2.20 with extracts from the BBC's original live
coverage including the procession from the palace to the abbey, the service
and crowning, and the procession through London, in Coronation Day. At 7.00,
still on BBC1, comes The Coronation - As If It Were Yesterday, introduced by
Sylvia Peters who hosted the BBC output on the day. This is a new
documentary recalling the occasion, as is ITV's two-hour Days Of Majesty
(8.00) probably the most enticing coronation item since its producers
include the excellent Peter Spry-Leverton. Finally, at midnight, comes The
Question Of Sovereignty (BBC2) in which a panel including Tony Benn and
Enoch Powell discuss how much sovereignty is left to the UK within the EC.
Timewatch (8.10 BBC2) talks to Britain's last living hangman and promises
'footage of the last working gallows in Britain'. How nice.
</TEXT>
