<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 93 / ITV companies fear takeover rule changes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AT LEAST three significant ITV companies will vigorously oppose any
immediate relaxation of the rules on ITV ownership, which prevent any of the
nine largest companies taking each other over.
The companies are Anglia, the ITV company for the east of England, HTV,
which covers Wales and the west, and Meridian, the south of England
franchise holder.
Anglia and HTV, medium-sized quoted ITV companies, are worried that they
could be taken over if the rules changed. Mr David McCall, Anglia chief
executive, said yesterday: 'I am not convinced by the economic arguments at
this stage that there need to be only four ITV companies.'
Anglia had a stronger balance sheet than some larger ITV companies and has
been expanding internationally through deals with Home Box Office of the US.
Mr Charles Romaine, chief executive of HTV, said ITV should be reviewed in
1996. 'We fear that the regional nature of ITV will disappear if changes are
made so quickly to ownership,' he said.
Lord Hollick, chairman of Meridian Broadcasting, also believes there should
be no piecemeal tinkering with the rules.
The Labour peer recently told the House of Lords he wanted an extension of
the moratorium on hostile takeovers of ITV companies that runs out in
December. He also called for a comprehensive review of the 1990 Broadcasting
Act in 1996.
Following intense lobbying by a number of the larger ITV companies, Mr Peter
Brooke, the National Heritage secretary plans to review ITV ownership rules.
He wants to examine the economic case that might justify the proposition
that ITV companies need to be bigger to compete internationally.
He intends to call a meeting of all the ITV companies to discuss the issue
and is likely to hear sharply conflicting views.
HTV is scathing about arguments that Pounds 100m could be saved each year by
the removal of unnecessary duplication in the ITV system.
The Independent Television Commission has made it clear that although it
will not oppose a relaxation of the ownership rules it will insist on
maintaining separate regional licences and the programme obligations that go
with them. This could limit potential savings.
The ownership issue is also likely to become political. Backbench MPs will
almost certainly be mobilised to oppose anything that would undermine the
separate existence of companies such as Anglia or HTV.
</TEXT>
