<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 93 / Holiday company clients face loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIX HUNDRED holidaymakers are in danger of losing money following the
collapse of Oxford-based SFV Holidays last month, according to the company
which has bought the SFV client list.
Kingsland Holidays, a Ply-mouth-based company that organises holidays in
France, said yesterday that it had bought the client list from liquidators
Berley and Co for an undisclosed sum.
Mr Simon Law, a Kingsland director, said: 'We have not bought SFV Holidays
in full, nor are we in a position to take on its debts. Our main
responsibility is to facilitate completion of endangered holiday bookings.'
The company estimates that 650 of SFV's 820 bookings in French villas were
made by credit card, which would enable customers to receive refunds. As
each booking was for a party of holidaymakers, Kingsland estimates the total
number of people who made bookings was 3,000. About 20 per cent did not book
by credit card and their only redress will be as ordinary creditors.
SFV was an unbonded company and had not arranged protection for customers.
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, had told the company it
was not required to protect clients' money because it was not a package
operator. This was because it allowed clients to choose their own ferry
crossings without assistance from the company.
Kingsland, a fully bonded member of the Association of Independent Tour
Operators, said it had been in touch with owners of self-catering
accommodation in France who had taken bookings from SFV. Mr Law said
property-owners were co-operating with Kingsland, even though some had not
received any payment from SFV.
</TEXT>
