<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 93 / BBC and Reuters plan TV service
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BBC WORLD Service Television and Reuters, the international news and
information group, are planning to launch a 24-hour-a-day satellite
television news service aimed at Latin America, Spain and the Hispanic
population of the US.
The two groups said yesterday they were negotiating with the Telemundo
Group, the Spanish-language television network that operates in the US. The
aim is to launch the service later this year. It would be beamed from Miami
by satellite to cable networks and broadcast stations throughout the
Americas.
A deal would mark a further stage in BBC World Service Television's strategy
of taking its service round the globe. It is already available throughout
Asia, in Africa and in Europe and plans are well advanced to launch in
Japan. Reuters has also been increasing its interests in television.
The new service would have two main sources of news. London-based Reuters
Television, formally Visnews, would provide international newsgathering
resources and BBC World Service Television would contribute international
news and programmes made for Spanish-speaking audiences in association with
the BBC's Latin American Service.
Mr Joaquin Blaya, president of Telemundo, said yesterday in New York the
formation of the service would be 'a milestone in Spanish-language
programming which would revolutionise Latin America from an information
point of view'.
