<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 93 / Finance warning on Tube services
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LONDON UNDERGROUND yesterday warned that improvements in service on London's
Underground network could be jeopardised if the government goes ahead with
reductions in investment announced in the Autumn Statement.
The company, announcing the results of the first year of the Underground's
Customer Charter, said that it had achieved all its service performance
targets for 1992-93. These covered train service, punctuality, cleanliness,
staff helpfulness, ticketing, escalator and escalator service and station
closures.
In some cases targets had been comfortably exceeded, with 91 per cent of
lifts in service during the peak hours compared with a target of 85 per
cent. The number of violent crimes against customers was 1.29 per million
journeys, compared with a target of 1.6 per million.
In the first year of its Customer Charter London Underground paid out just
more than Pounds 68,000 in refunds for delays of 20 minutes or more which
were the company's responsibility.
Targets for most performance indicators will be increased next year with
much higher standards of train cleanliness, information for passengers and
reliability of train services and lifts.
But Mr Denis Tunnicliffe, managing director, said efficient management alone
could not sustain service improvements if investment fell.
He said: 'The key to a decently modern metro is good management and the
right level of investment.'
Mr Steven Norris, minister for transport in London, said he shared London
Underground's disappointment at funding. He promised to battle with the
Treasury to secure the best possible deal in the next public expenditure
round in the autumn.
</TEXT>
