FT  02 JUN 93 / Satellite dish ownership at 2.15m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SATELLITE DISH ownership increased by 52,000 between February and March to a
total of 2.15m according to the latest figures from GfK, the market research
group, Raymond Snoddy writes.
The study, commissioned by the ITV Association, also estimates that between
June and December last year there was a rise of 290,000 subscribers to the
pay channels of British Sky Broadcasting.
The group estimates that by the end of the year there were 1.1m subscribers
to Sky Sports and adds that only 13 per cent of survey respondents said the
sports channel was a significant incentive to purchase a satellite dish.
The research is based on a six-monthly ownership survey of 10,000 homes
updated by monthly sales information. The survey does not cover Northern
Ireland, the Isle of Man or the Channel Islands.
The latest figure for June, from Barb, which provides official broadcasting
ratings, estimates that there are 2.44m homes with satellite dishes in the
UK, with a further 694,000 receiving satellite channels from cable systems.
Mr Andrew Quinn, chief executive of the ITV Association, yesterday accused
BSkyB - in which Pearson, owner of the Financial Times, has a significant
stake - of over-stating the number of satellite homes.
