<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 93 / Brewers urge cut in beer excise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GUY DE JONQUIERES, Consumer Industries Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BREWING industry is urging the government to lower the new rate of
excise duty on beer, which took effect yesterday, on the grounds that it
breaches a pledge by ministers that it would not raise more revenue than the
previous system.
The Brewers' Society said that if the new system had been applied over the
past 12 months it would have yielded Pounds 64m - or 3 per cent - more than
the old one.
The society said ministers had promised that the rate would be fiscally
neutral and would be rectified if that proved not to be the case. It called
on the government to change the rate before the November Budget.
Customs and Excise expressed surprise that the brewers had not complained
earlier and said they had not substantiated their claim. It said the new
rate had been calculated in consultation with the society after a survey of
brewers.
The approximate rate had been indicated to the society a year ago and
confirmed in early March. The society had not challenged it until three
weeks ago, however, and had produced supporting data only last Friday.
The society said it was unsure until recently how the system would work. But
Customs and Excise said all the details had been settled three months ago,
except for a minor question concerning warehouses.
Customs and Excise also pointed out that the revenue neutrality of the rate
would depend on the types of beer being sold. It said ministers would
examine before the next Budget any data supplied by the society.
The new system charges duty on the volume and alcoholic strength of beer
production instead of on the gravity of liquid before fermentation.
</TEXT>
