<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 93 / Brown calls for overdraft charge inquiry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN INQUIRY into the system of charges operated by the high street clearing
banks was demanded yesterday by Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, who
said charges for unauthorised overdrafts were 'little short of usurious'.
He warned Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, that millions of consumers
would be shocked by the levels of charges, and would expect protection from
him.
The condemnation came on the day that National Westminster Bank became the
first of Britain's big four banks to introduce a charge of Pounds 3.50 a day
on current account holders who overdraw 'substantially' without authority.
According to calculations carried out for Mr Brown by the House of Commons
library, NatWest is making charges equivalent to an annualised percentage
rate of interest (APR) of 369 per cent for an unauthorised overdraft of
Pounds 1,000.
The calculations include both interest charged on overdrafts and
administrative charges. Mr Brown said the NatWest charge for an unauthorised
Pounds 100 overdraft was equivalent to an APR of more than 1m per cent.
The figures suggest that at Barclays an unauthorised overdraft of Pounds 100
would attract charges equivalent to an APR of 961 per cent, at Lloyds 238
per cent, and at Midland 733 per cent.
Mr Brown dismissed criticism of his calculations, saying charges, commission
and interest rates all contributed to the cost of borrowing.
Total charges for the top eight banks, he added, were more than Pounds
6.2bn, compared with just more than Pounds 4bn before the recession started
two-and-a-half years ago.
Among the remedies which Mr Brown urged were a right to be told the details
of charges in advance, recourse to a statutory ombudsman and the right to
information about bank charges in the form of a league table.
NatWest said yesterday it did not understand how a figure of 1m per cent APR
could be reached under its charging structure. It said rates for
unauthorised overdrafts were clearly set out in advance for its customers.
</TEXT>
