<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 93 / Britain out of ERM due to poor preparation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S failure to stay in the European exchange rate mechanism was in
large part due to poor preparation by Mr John Major, then chancellor, before
entry in October 1990, Lord Lawson, the former Tory chancellor says in an
article published today, Emma Tucker writes.
In the London Business School's International Financial Outlook Lord Lawson
says that the UK joined the ERM at too high a rate. He criticises the
government for inadequately agreeing entry terms with the Bundesbank
beforehand.
'Sterling joined at a rate which the Bundesbank regarded from the outset as
too high and which it therefore felt no great moral obligation to support -
a fact that was later to become all too apparent to the financial markets,'
he says.
Lord Lawson also says there is no conceivable gradual 'glide-path' to allow
an exchange rate system to transform imperceptibly into a single currency.
</TEXT>
