<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 93 / Labour in control of council body
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR HAS won overall control of the Association of County Councils for the
first time in the organisation's 104-year history, John Authers writes.
The development - which follows the Conservatives' disastrous showing in
last month's county council elections when they lost control of all but one
of the 20 counties they were defending - intensifies the difficulties facing
Mr John Gummer, the new environment secretary, in his dealings with local
government.
Labour's majority was assured yesterday when a selection panel at hung
Cheshire county council gave the party two seats on the ACC executive, with
one each for the Tories and the Liberal Democrats. This ensures the party of
an overall majority of five seats on the ACC's executive council. The
Conservatives are now the ACC's third-largest party.
This puts Labour in charge of three of the four main representative bodies
for local government in mainland Britain. The Association of Metropolitan
Authorities and the Convention of Scottish Local Authorities are Labour
controlled, while the Association of District Councils remains under a
minority Tory leadership.
Labour's strength on the ACC was boosted last week by a decision of
Labour-controlled Derbyshire county council to rejoin the association after
a 12-year gap, giving the party an extra three seats.
