<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 93 / Property debt sale urged by Bank
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BANK of England yesterday urged banks to consider selling their loans to
property companies in the form of property-backed bonds.
Mr Pen Kent, an associate director of the Bank of England, said that
converting debt into securities 'frees the way for property companies to
raise new capital, refinance debt and strengthen their own balance sheets,
and in some instances injects liquidity into the market'.
Speaking at the launch of the Association of Property Bankers Mr Kent for
the first time gave qualified support to the newly created market in
distressed corporate debt.
In an speech last year Mr Kent concentrated on the potential pitfalls for a
company in financial difficulties if that company's banks decided to sell
the loans they had made to it. Yesterday, however, he said that the sale of
the debt to new investors had 'the potential for a beneficial and productive
effect for a company in difficulties'.
New investors might have expertise relevant to the company or might be able
to take a longer-term view of the returns to be made from the debt than the
company's bankers.
Mr Kent made two suggestions aimed at reducing the risk that banks would
repeat their 1980s error of acquiring excessive exposure to property in
different parts of the country.
He asked whether 'banks would benefit from a closer awareness of the
planning and development process'.
He also invited bankers to comment on whether it would be useful for new and
more detailed statistics to be gathered on property lending and how this
could be done.
</TEXT>
