<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 93 / Mates brought in by Nadir PR adviser
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON, JIMMY BURNS and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MICHAEL Mates first took an interest in Mr Asil Nadir, the fugitive
businessman, after an approach by Mr Mark Rogerson, one of Mr Nadir's public
relations advisers.
In a statement issued on Monday Mr Mates, the minister who is at the centre
of a political row over his relationship with the founder of the Polly Peck
business empire, said he had been approached to take an interest in Mr
Nadir's affairs by a 'a constituent who was one of Mr Nadir's advisers'.
It emerged yesterday that the constituent was Mr Rogerson, a former BBC
journalist and founder of Morgan &amp; Rogerson, a public relations firm which
advises Mr Nadir.
Mr Nadir last month jumped his Pounds 3.5m bail and fled to northern Cyprus.
Mr Rogerson said yesterday that he had approached Mr Mates, a minister in
the Northern Ireland office, because he had understood that Mr Mates was a
'good MP'.
Mr Rogerson and his partner, Mr Christopher Morgan, are convinced that Mr
Nadir has received unjust treatment from the British legal system since he
was charged in December 1990 with theft and false accounting.
Mr Morgan has known Mr Mates for several years. Mr Rogerson said yesterday
that he had never met Mr Mates before talking to him about Mr Nadir.
The first meeting between Mr Mates and Mr Rogerson took place 18 months ago
and there have been several subsequent meetings.
Mr Mates has also discussed the Serious Fraud Office's handling of Mr
Nadir's case with Mr Anthony Scrivener QC, Mr Nadir's defence counsel.
Mr Scrivener said yesterday that he could not recall any reference to an
introduction by a constituent when Mr Mates approached him.
In his statement on Monday Mr Mates said that 'a constituent who was one of
Nadir's advisers' contacted him about 18 months ago 'raising certain
matters' about the SFO's handling of the case and the delay in bringing it
to court.
Mr Mates has said that he subsequently had meetings with the
attorney-general and there had been 'an exchange of correspondence' on the
subject, throughout which he had been 'consulted and advised ' by Mr
Scrivener.
Mr Scrivener said he could not recall the first time he had been approached
by Mr Mates other than it was 'possibly' before the last election.
He said: 'Mr Mates was very heated (about the SFO treatment) . . . I don't
know about a constituent . . . Mr Mates appeared out of the blue.'
Mr Scrivener defended Mr Mates's action, which he described as the
'absolutely correct action' by an MP on the side of justice.
Mr Mates received the support of a colleague in the Northern Ireland office
yesterday when Mr Robert Atkins, a junior minister, said that the matter was
not one that required Mr Mates's resignation, and that he was sure his
colleague would come through the affair 'with flying colours'.
Some other Conservative MPs were less supportive, however, and said that the
connection with Mr Nadir put a question mark over Mr Mates's judgment.
The minister's statement, in which he said he had acted on behalf of a
constituent and that he had given a watch to Mr Nadir as a light-hearted
gift, has so far failed to silence his critics.
Labour MPs have already said that they intend to increase the pressure on Mr
John Major to investigate Mr Mates's actions in connection with Mr Nadir
when the Commons returns next week.
</TEXT>
