<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 93 / High street banks cut private-sector loans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PROLONGED recession, loan write-offs and increased caution about the risks
of lending contributed to a Pounds 4.8bn fall in lending by the big high
street banks to private-sector companies last year, it emerged yesterday.
The British Bankers' Association disclosed in its annual abstract that the
loans outstanding to industrial and commercial companies totalled Pounds
65.6bn at the end of December, compared with Pounds 70.4bn at the same time
in 1991.
The lending by the banks - Abbey National, Bank of Scotland, Barclays,
Lloyds, Midland, National Westminster, Standard Chartered, Royal Bank of
Scotland and TSB Group - was largely reduced through a fall in overdrafts.
Overdrafts to industrial and commercial companies fell by Pounds 3.8bn to
Pounds 23.6bn. The fall in lending to private-sector companies came despite
an increase in lending to individuals and households from Pounds 117.5bn in
1991 to Pounds 123.6bn last year.
The BBA said the fall in lending reflected 'serious attempts' by
private-sector companies to reduce their indebtedness, both by running down
their deposits and by transferring debt into equity.
The high street banks - which account for 70 per cent of British sterling
lending - also closed some 700 branches and cut 18,500 staff as they
struggled to cut over-capacity in their branch and distribution networks.
The BBA disclosed that the banks cut the total number of branches by 5.7 per
cent and the total number of staff by 5.6 per cent during 1992. The cuts in
the banks' 11,600-branch network have been continuing this year and are
expected to last at least until 1995.
The report said that lending figures had been distorted by loan write-offs
totalling Pounds 4.5bn. Most of the write-offs were on troubled loans to
property, construction and manufacturing companies.
The banks increased the share of their lending allocated to mortgages.
House-purchase loans increased to 33.2 per cent of total sterling lending of
Pounds 272.5bn, compared with 31.3 per cent of total lending of Pounds
268.2bn in 1991.
They also achieved a substantial increase in their share of the mortgage
market. While net lending for house purchases from building societies fell
to Pounds 13.7bn last year from Pounds 20.9bn in 1991, that of banks rose to
Pounds 5.9bn from Pounds 4.7bn.
The fall in the number of bank branches was partly offset by an increase of
600 in the number of automated teller machines in high streets. Total cash
withdrawn from the 15,000 bank cash machines rose 8.6 per cent.
The average credit outstanding on Mastercard and Visa credit cards continued
to rise, from Pounds 407 in 1991 to Pounds 419 last year, although it grew
more slowly than in previous years.
</TEXT>
