<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 93 / S African politicians fight to keep talks on track
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATTI WALDMEIR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SOUTH African politicians last night battled to keep the constitutional
negotiating process on track as negotiators finally began to discuss
fundamental issues such as the process for writing a new constitution.
Negotiators acknowledged that they had failed to achieve sufficient progress
on constitutional issues to announce a firm date for the first multi-racial
elections tomorrow, as had been expected. They postponed a meeting of the
208-member negotiating forum, charged with announcing a date, until 25 June.
But they held out hopes that a target election date could be announced
instead, with the date to be finalised only once agreement had been reached
on a constitution under which elections could be held.
The government and the ANC are keen to announce a date by their self-imposed
deadline of tomorrow - even if it is just a target date - to avoid a
threatened outbreak of mass action and violence.
The ANC's youth leader, Mr Peter Mokaba, had threatened that black
youngsters would make the country ungovernable unless an election date was
set by Thursday.
Negotiators from the 26 parties represented at the multi-party forum
yesterday took a step towards narrowing the differences between them on
constitutional issues when the Inkatha Freedom Party agreed in principle to
accept an elected constituent assembly to draft a final constitution.
This represents a fundamental shift in the negotiating position of Inkatha;
but final agreement will be conditional on agreement to grant significant
powers to regional government under a new constitution. Negotiators are due
to discuss this issue, the crux of the constitutional problem, tomorrow.
The ANC also made a significant concession, agreeing that the powers of
regional governments should be agreed by the 26-party forum rather than an
elected assembly. This process is likely to favour the interests of Inkatha.
Meanwhile, negotiators faced further delays over the issue of whether the
Pan Africanist Congress should be excluded from the talks. Government
insists that the PAC should be ejected from the talks because it has refused
to abandon its armed struggle.
</TEXT>
