FT  02 JUN 93 / UN relief convoy attacked two dead
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Two Danish drivers and a local interpreter were killed, and four Danes
wounded, yesterday when artillery fire hit their UN relief convoy in
northern Bosnia, a UN spokesman said, Reuter reports from Geneva.
The 12-truck convoy, carrying food to the northern Bosnian town of Maglaj,
was unloading supplies when shells landed at the mouth of the tunnel on the
road south of Maglaj, said a Geneva spokesman of the UN High Commissioner
for Refugees.
Meanwhile, the bodies of two Italians - reported to have been shot while
delivering food aid in central Bosnia on Saturday - were found yesterday. A
third Italian also thought to have been shot was still missing.
In Sarajevo, two shells landed on a football match, killing at least 11
people and wounding about 100. The players thought the pitch was safe as it
was surrounded by apartment buildings. One of the wounded said he was
convinced the target was deliberately chosen.
