<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 93 / Finland to introduce 22% VAT
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FINLAND plans to introduce value added tax next January, at a general rate
of 22 per cent, to help trim government debt and bring the country into line
with the European Community, which Finland hopes to join in 1995, Hugh
Carnegy writes from Stockholm.
Assuming parliament approves, VAT will replace a turnover tax currently
levied at the same rate. But it will cover an extended range of services.
Exemptions are planned on health, social, educational, banking and insurance
services, and on agriculture and forestry.
